Q.1 ARIMA process

  1. Parametrization of h[.]

  2. AR(2) model : \[ H_1(q^{-1}) = \frac{1}{1 - 0.8q^{-1} + 0.12q^{-2}} \]

Factorizing the denominator , we get

\[H_1(q^{-1}) = \frac{1}{(1 - 0.6q^{-1})(1 - 0.2q^{-1})}\] Therefore

\[H_1 (q^{-1}) = \frac{1}{2}\left( \frac{3}{1-(0.6)q^{-1}} - \frac{1}{1-0.2q^{-1}} \right)\]

From binomial expansion, we get

\[H_1 (q^{-1}) = \frac{1}{2}\left( 3\sum_{n=0}^{\infty} 0.6^n q^{-n} - \sum_{n=0}^{\infty} 0.2^nq^{-n}\right)\] Therefore,

\[h[n] = \frac{1}{2}\left( 3*0.6^n - 0.2^n\right) ......\forall n \geq 0 \]

  1. ARMA(1,1) process \[H_2(q^{-1}) = \frac{1 + 0.3q^{-1}}{1 - 0.6q^{-1}}\] After binomial expansion of the given transfer function operator, we get

\[H(q^{-1}) = (1+0.3q^{-1})(\sum_{n = 0}^\infty 0.6^n q^{-n})\]

Therfore

\[h[n] = 0.6^n + 0.3(0.6^n).....\forall n > 0 \]

  1. The given process

\[v[k] = -d_1v[k-1] + e[k]\] In the above equation substituting the value of \(v[k-1]\) and \(v[k-2]\) subsequently, we get

\[v[k] = -d_1^3v[k-3] + e[k] -d_1e[k-1] + d_1^2e[k-2]\]

Therefore

\[ \hat{v}[k|k-3] = -d_1^3v[k-3]\] Therefore

\[ error = v[k] - \hat{v}[k|k-3]\]

\[ error = e[k] -d_1e[k-1] + d_1^2e[k-2]\]

\[ \sigma_{error} = (1 + d_1^2 + d_1^4)\sigma_e^2 \] ###Q.2 Computing correlations

The given process is

\[y[k] = \frac{b_2^0q^{-2}}{1+f_1^0q^{-1}}u[k] + e[k] \] where, u[k] and e[k] both are Gaussian WN processes with zero mean.

Therefore, $E(y[k]) = 0 $

\[ \sigma_{yy}[l] = E(y[k]y[[k-l]) = -f_1^0\sigma_{yy}[l-1] + b_2^0\sigma_{uy}[l-2] + \sigma_{ey}[l] + f_1^0\sigma_{ey}[l-1]\] Substituting the values for lag = 0 and 1, we get

\[ \sigma_{yy}[0] = -f_1^0\sigma_{yy}[1] + b_2^0\sigma_{uy}[2] + \sigma_e^2 .....(1)\]

\[\sigma_{yy}[1] = -f_1^0\sigma_{yy}[0] + b_2^0\sigma_{uy}[1] + f_1^0\sigma_e^2 . . . . .(2)\] \[\sigma_{yu}[l] = E(y[k]u[k-l]) = -f_1^0\sigma_{yu}[l-1] + b_2^0\sigma_{uu}[l-2] .......(3)\]

\[\sigma_{yu}[1] = -f_1^0\sigma_{yu}[0].....(4)\] \[\sigma_{yu}[0] = -f_1^0\sigma_{yu}[1] . . ....(5)\] \[\sigma_{yu}[2] = -f_1^0\sigma_{yu}[1] + b_2^0\sigma_{uu}[0].....(6)\] From equation (4) & (5), we get

\[\sigma_{yu}[0] = \sigma_{yu}[1] = 0\] From equation (6), we get

\[\sigma_{yu}[2] = b_2^0\sigma_u^2\] Solving for (1) and (2) we get

\[\sigma_{y}^2 = \frac{(b_2^0)^2}{1-(f_1^0)^2}\sigma_u^2 +\sigma_e^2\]

Also,

\[\sigma_{yy}[1] = (b_2^0)^2 \frac{-f_1^0}{1-(f_1^0)^2}\sigma^2_u\]

From equation (3), substituting the value of lag = 3, we get

\[\sigma_{yu}[3] = -f_1^0\sigma_{yu}[2] = - b_2^0f_1^0\sigma_u^2\] Similarly for lag = 4, we get

\[\sigma_{yu}[3] = -f_1^0\sigma_{yu}[3] = b_2^0(f_1^0)^2\sigma_u^2\] Therefore we can see that,

\[\frac{\sigma_{yu}[l]}{\sigma_{yu}[2]} = (-f_1^0)^{l-2} .....\forall l\geq2\]

Since, \(|f_0^1| < 1\) therefore above correlation we keep decreasing with lag. Hence it will be maximum at lag = 2.

We know that the delay is observed at maximum correlation, therefore we can say that the delay between \(y[k]\) and \(u[k]\) is 2.

Q.3 Process with Trend

Given series is of the type

\[v[k] = \beta_0 + \beta_1k + w[k]\] where, \(w[k]\) is stationary ARMA process

For the above type of series two different ways a model can be build 1. Filtering approach 2. Differencing approach

The filtering approach relies on estimation of trend followed by the development of an ARMA model for the stationary residuals. The differencing approach, in contrast, eliminates the trend implicitly and fits an ARMA model.

Another difference is that an ARIMA model fixes one of the poles of the model to the unit circle irrespective of whether the actual process has a pole on the unit circle or not.

The above process has its own merits and demerits:

The merit is that the estimation of “stationary” poles, but close to unit circle, can result in models with confidence regions containing non-stationary models.By forcing the pole to the unit circle a priori, this situation is avoided.

The demerits are however that a stationary process with slowly decaying process acquires a non-stationary representation.

In system identification, differencing has to be carried out with caution since it amplifies the noise levels in the differenced data thereby decreasing the SNR

However single degree of differencing introduces a non-inverible zero in the differenced series

library(MLmetrics)
## 
## Attaching package: 'MLmetrics'
## The following object is masked from 'package:base':
## 
##     Recall
# Loading and Plotting the given data 

load("a3_q4.Rdata")

plot(wk)

train = wk[1:800] # Training purpose 

test = wk[801:1000] #Test data 

#List of the Box - Cox transformation parameters 
lambda_v = seq(-5,5,0.001)

#Empty matrix for list mse values 
mse_v = {}

index = 0 


for (lambda in lambda_v) {
  
  index = index + 1
  
  if (lambda == 0){
    
    bxcx = log(wk)
  }
  
  else{
    
    bxcx = ((wk)^lambda -1)/lambda
    
    #Fitting an AR model on the first 800 observations
    armod = ar(bxcx[1:800], aic = TRUE, order.max = 7)
    
    #One step ahead prediction using filter routine 
    test_filter = filter(test, armod$ar, method = "convolution", sides =1 )
    
    #Trimming the first 'NA' values appearing due to filtering 
    mse_v[index] =  MSE(test_filter[(1+armod$order):200],          test[(1+armod$order):200])
    
  }
}

#Plotting Mean Squared error on each lambda wrt lambda
plot( lambda_v, mse_v)

#Finding the optimal lambda 

opt_lambda = lambda_v[which.min(mse_v)]
print(opt_lambda)
## [1] 2.928

The above value is the value of the optimal \(\lambda\) corresponding to the case where MSE is minimum.
